  "prompt": "What is frictional force?",
  "response": "Frictional force is a resistive force that opposes the relative motion or tendency of such motion between two surfaces in contact. It arises due to the interactions between the molecules and irregularities on the surfaces of the objects. Friction plays a crucial role in everyday life, enabling activities like walking, driving, and gripping objects.\n\nHere are the key types of frictional force:\n\n1. **Static Friction**:  \n   This acts on objects at rest and prevents them from starting to move. It adjusts to match the applied force until the force exceeds the maximum static friction, causing the object to move.\n\n2. **Kinetic Friction (Sliding Friction)**:  \n   This acts on objects that are already in motion. It opposes the direction of movement and is generally less than static friction.\n\n3. **Rolling Friction**:  \n   This occurs when an object rolls over a surface, such as a wheel on the ground. It is typically much smaller than sliding friction.\n\n4. **Fluid Friction**:  \n   This acts on objects moving through fluids (liquids or gases) and is often referred to as drag or viscous force.\n\n### Factors Affecting Frictional Force:  \n- **Nature of the Surfaces**: Rougher surfaces generally have higher friction.  \n- **Normal Force**: Friction is directly proportional to the force pressing the surfaces together (the normal force).  \n- **Surface Area**: For most cases, friction is independent of the contact area.  \n\n### Mathematical Representation:  \nFrictional force (\\(F_f\\)) is calculated using:  \n\\[ F_f = \\mu \\cdot N \\]  \nwhere:  \n- \\( \\mu \\) = coefficient of friction (depends on the materials and type of friction),  \n- \\( N \\) = normal force (the force perpendicular to the contact surfaces).\n\nFrictional force is essential for motion control, energy dissipation, and maintaining stability in various systems.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
